Here's the complete migration. Your code has three `Thread.Abort`-related patterns — all are eliminated in ASP.NET Core.

---

## Pattern Inventory

| Pattern | Location | Replacement |
|---------|----------|-------------|
| `Response.End()` | `btnExport_Click` | Return `FileContentResult` — no need to end the response |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` ×3 | `btnRedirect_Click` | Return `RedirectResult` — MVC handles the response |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `btnRedirect_Click` | Remove entirely — no abort exceptions exist in Core |

---

## Migrated Code (ASP.NET Core / .NET 8)

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;
using System.Text;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();

        // Return a file result — the framework handles Content-Type,
        // Content-Disposition, and completing the response. No Response.End() needed.
        return File(
            Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data),
            "text/csv",
            "report.csv");
    }

    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Redirect()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            return Redirect("/login");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }
}
```

---

## What Changed and Why

### 1. `Response.End()` → return `File(...)`
In WebForms, `Response.End()` calls `Thread.Abort` internally to stop the pipeline. In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`. In ASP.NET Core MVC, you simply **return an `IActionResult`** — the framework writes the response and completes it for you.

### 2. `Response.Redirect(url, true)` → return `Redirect(url)`
The `true` (endResponse) parameter triggered `Thread.Abort` to halt execution after the redirect header was set. In ASP.NET Core, `return Redirect(url)` short-circuits the action method naturally via the `return` statement — no thread abort needed.

### 3. `catch (ThreadAbortException)` → removed
This catch block only existed to swallow the exception that `Response.Redirect(url, true)` threw. Since the new code uses `return Redirect(...)`, no abort exception is thrown, so the catch block is dead code. **Remove it entirely** — don't replace it with `catch (OperationCanceledException)`, which has a different purpose (cooperative cancellation of async work).

---

## Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Calling `HttpContext.Response.Redirect()` instead of returning `Redirect()`** | The `HttpContext.Response.Redirect()` method still exists in Core, but it doesn't stop execution. Code after the call **continues running**. Always prefer returning an `IActionResult`. |
| **Null-reference on `User.Identity`** | In Core, `User.Identity` can be `null` if no authentication middleware is configured. Use null-conditional: `User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true`. |
| **Missing `[Authorize]` attribute** | Instead of manual `IsAuthenticated` checks, consider `[Authorize]` on the action/controller — the middleware handles the redirect to login automatically. |
| **`Response.Write` / `Response.Clear` don't exist** | These WebForms APIs have no direct equivalent. Use `IActionResult` subtypes (`FileResult`, `ContentResult`, etc.) which handle response writing. |
| **Forgetting `CancellationToken` for long-running work** | If `GenerateReport()` or `ProcessRequest()` are expensive, accept `CancellationToken` and pass `HttpContext.RequestAborted` so work stops if the client disconnects. |

---

## Optional: Adding Request Cancellation Support

If `GenerateReport()` is long-running, wire up `HttpContext.RequestAborted`:

```csharp
[HttpPost]
public async Task<IActionResult> Export(CancellationToken cancellationToken)
{
    // ASP.NET Core automatically binds HttpContext.RequestAborted here
    var data = await GenerateReportAsync(cancellationToken);
    return File(Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data), "text/csv", "report.csv");
}
```

This gives you cooperative cancellation — the modern replacement for `Thread.Abort` — where the framework signals the token when the client disconnects, and your code checks it voluntarily.
